  <h1>Common Rideshare Accident Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Uber/Lyft&rsquo;s $1M coverage always applies.&rdquo;</h2><p>Only in Periods 2 and 3. If the driver&rsquo;s app was off or they were waiting for a request (Period 1), the $1M doesn&rsquo;t apply. The phase at the exact moment of impact is what matters.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The driver&rsquo;s personal insurance covers everything.&rdquo;</h2><p>Most personal auto policies have commercial use exclusions that deny coverage when the driver is using the vehicle for hire. This is the coverage gap the rideshare companies&rsquo; Period 1 contingent coverage is designed to address — but it&rsquo;s not as comprehensive as Periods 2/3.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can sue Uber or Lyft directly for the driver&rsquo;s negligence.&rdquo;</h2><p>Direct vicarious liability claims against Uber/Lyft for driver negligence are generally barred by the independent contractor classification. Claims are made against the rideshare company&rsquo;s insurance program, not the company as an employer. Direct claims (negligent hiring, entrustment) require specific additional facts.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Taking an ambulance means I accepted blame.&rdquo;</h2><p>No. Accepting medical treatment has no bearing on your claim for reimbursement. Seek medical care if you need it — always. Medical treatment records document your injuries; refusing care can hurt your damages claim.</p>
